WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:11.840
Thank you and my co-presenter as well John is here. He will not be presenting

00:00:11.840 --> 00:00:21.120
because he can't be bothered I guess. Is this better? Yeah he works for the

00:00:21.120 --> 00:00:33.439
Department of Ed and we work together in... John works for the Department of

00:00:33.439 --> 00:00:41.160
Education and we work together in Chi-Square Lab. So that's about us. So I'm

00:00:41.160 --> 00:00:44.599
gonna set the context and by the way this talk isn't actually... I teach data

00:00:44.599 --> 00:00:48.919
science but this talk is not about teaching data science. It's about using

00:00:48.919 --> 00:00:54.119
data science to teach. That's sort of the essence of what we do in learning

00:00:54.119 --> 00:01:00.080
analytics. We collect data from educational interactions and then we

00:01:00.080 --> 00:01:06.639
analyze that and try to provide feedback to instructors. And the story here is as

00:01:06.639 --> 00:01:11.239
we all know there was a pandemic in Argentina. We went into full lockdown in

00:01:11.239 --> 00:01:18.360
March of 2020 and then that meant that all instructions needed to be online in

00:01:18.360 --> 00:01:22.440
a hurry. Since we're in the southern hemisphere this actually coincided

00:01:22.440 --> 00:01:25.680
pretty much with the beginning of the semester so we didn't have to do it mid

00:01:25.680 --> 00:01:32.239
semester. But what happened is that everyone started to teach using Zoom or

00:01:32.239 --> 00:01:39.000
any kind of video conferencing system that was available and we found that

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:44.559
less than half the students actually had access to a laptop. So in practice they

00:01:44.559 --> 00:01:51.519
were going to follow the course on a device, on an Android phone typically.

00:01:51.519 --> 00:02:03.000
And so what we wanted to do, and this is something that we worked on before, is to

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:07.480
help them create, help the instructors create a feedback loop. Because as Kelly

00:02:07.480 --> 00:02:12.919
mentioned in her talk there is a lot of nonverbal communication that goes on

00:02:12.919 --> 00:02:16.559
when you actually meet face-to-face. That's part of the reason we're all here.

00:02:16.559 --> 00:02:22.039
And you lose that, you lose some of it at least when you do video conferencing.

00:02:22.039 --> 00:02:25.279
Especially if the class is a big class with a hundred students or something

00:02:25.279 --> 00:02:30.800
like that. So what we set out to do was to mitigate some of this by creating a

00:02:30.800 --> 00:02:37.440
tool to to provide feedback so the students could provide feedback to the

00:02:37.440 --> 00:02:44.199
instructor. And we did three iterations of this. One was slapped together very

00:02:44.199 --> 00:02:51.919
quickly because we were in a hurry in I think less than a week. And then we did,

00:02:51.919 --> 00:02:58.559
called that the emergency alpha. And then we did a proper alpha version in April.

00:02:58.559 --> 00:03:06.919
And then we did what I would call a beta version in August of 2021. So for the

00:03:06.919 --> 00:03:15.679
start of that semester. And the first one we did in Shiny using a package

00:03:15.679 --> 00:03:22.000
called Shiny Mobile. And then we hooked it up to a backend and we we have a

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:27.360
package called Cognito R that allows for password protection of Shiny apps that

00:03:27.360 --> 00:03:32.360
we used. It's available on CRAN if you want to use it. And then we distributed

00:03:32.360 --> 00:03:40.559
that as a PWA. And this is what it looks like. So essentially the two, on the left

00:03:40.559 --> 00:03:46.320
there, the two icons are just links to two Shiny apps. One for the instructor

00:03:46.320 --> 00:03:52.720
and one for the student. And they have a login and that's handled by by Amazon. And

00:03:52.720 --> 00:03:59.320
then we have a really easy questionnaire with some some questions. One of them was

00:03:59.320 --> 00:04:05.759
about connectivity because it turned out to be important in this context. And

00:04:05.759 --> 00:04:10.240
then there's two open-ended questions there. You know, what did you learn in

00:04:10.240 --> 00:04:15.960
this class and what would you like to to have reviewed? And this goes back and

00:04:15.960 --> 00:04:21.799
gets analyzed and we use R for that. And then we provide feedback to the

00:04:21.799 --> 00:04:27.200
instructor on, you know, the student feedback is summarized and provided back

00:04:27.200 --> 00:04:33.720
to the instructor. And this is the same package, Shiny Mobile. It provides

00:04:33.720 --> 00:04:41.839
interface items that look good on a cell phone. So and this is a

00:04:41.839 --> 00:04:49.000
completely, you know, completely reasonable way of putting a Shiny app on

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:54.959
on a cell phone. It works, it updates very quickly. It's very lightweight. It's

00:04:54.959 --> 00:04:59.000
only a link and it's cross-platform. It works on an iPhone, it works on on

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:05.320
anything that can show a web page. We did find though some bandwidth issues

00:05:05.320 --> 00:05:11.839
because if everyone tries to log on to, we published this to shiny.io, if

00:05:11.839 --> 00:05:15.000
everyone tries to log on at the same time to provide feedback, it actually

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:21.839
crashes the server. Now you can solve that by, you know, by throwing hardware at

00:05:21.920 --> 00:05:27.640
it, but that's not really scalable. So and you know, I was also a little

00:05:27.640 --> 00:05:31.920
uncomfortable that this is not a native app. You can't send people to the Play

00:05:31.920 --> 00:05:39.440
Store or App Store to get it. So the second version, we use the templates from

00:05:39.440 --> 00:05:44.799
the Android community and there's several of them floating around. And

00:05:44.799 --> 00:05:49.279
there's one that we have that we used that you can see there on the

00:05:49.279 --> 00:05:57.799
slide. It's essentially a wrapper that displays a web page. But this one goes on

00:05:57.799 --> 00:06:05.519
the Play Store and, you know, you need to know a little bit of Java. And if you

00:06:05.519 --> 00:06:10.720
hate Python, you probably hate Java as well. But it's like two lines, so it's not

00:06:10.720 --> 00:06:16.559
that bad. And it's still just a Shiny app in a wrapper, so it's still not

00:06:16.559 --> 00:06:21.200
really scalable. And it will only work for Android, which is a slight

00:06:21.200 --> 00:06:29.359
drawback. So this is a slide from one of the instructors who used the app. And

00:06:29.359 --> 00:06:34.959
this is what it looks like. This is probably a later iteration. And so

00:06:34.959 --> 00:06:40.640
she used this to show her students the feedback that she was

00:06:40.640 --> 00:06:44.760
getting from them and show them that this is actually useful and, you know,

00:06:44.760 --> 00:06:51.679
what did we learn. And as you can see, you know, it's summarized in not a

00:06:51.679 --> 00:06:57.399
word cloud format, because that wouldn't really look good on a device. So we

00:06:57.399 --> 00:07:06.000
used some other tools there. And we got research results from this, which

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:11.519
show they were quite encouraging. And so the scale here is 0 to 10. That's how

00:07:11.519 --> 00:07:17.959
it's graded in Argentina. Anything below, so 4 is the lowest passing grade. So

00:07:17.959 --> 00:07:23.079
that part of the scale isn't actually being used. And so, you know, the

00:07:23.079 --> 00:07:27.839
distributions are not normal. And there were some outliers like you could see. So

00:07:27.839 --> 00:07:32.839
we, you know, we use candles for correlations. And then we use ordinal

00:07:32.839 --> 00:07:38.279
regression instead of linear regression. And we found during simulation that we

00:07:38.279 --> 00:07:43.200
could actually predict. This is post-hoc though, but we had predictive power. After

00:07:43.200 --> 00:07:46.600
just three weeks, we could pretty much tell which students were going to finish

00:07:46.600 --> 00:07:51.559
the course. And we got good feedback from the instructors. They said, you know, this

00:07:51.559 --> 00:07:58.519
is actually useful for us. There are some issues. Some of them were

00:07:58.519 --> 00:08:04.160
actually mentioned in the last talk. There's a lot of linguistic

00:08:04.160 --> 00:08:09.839
models that you can get access to, but they are typically either too general or

00:08:09.839 --> 00:08:17.359
too specific. When you're teaching class, and the example here is class in

00:08:17.359 --> 00:08:24.760
linguistics, introductory linguistics, it's often very specific vocabulary that

00:08:24.760 --> 00:08:30.880
you have to learn. And that will always sort of mess up the statistical

00:08:30.920 --> 00:08:36.359
models that have been trained on, you know, a billion words. Because this is, you

00:08:36.359 --> 00:08:40.000
know, these are words that you use in two papers in your life. And then you

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:45.159
don't repeat them. And then there is the issue of Spanish versus English that we

00:08:45.159 --> 00:08:50.200
actually saw some of in the last post. We did most of this in Spanish,

00:08:50.200 --> 00:08:56.440
obviously, but we are also working on an English language version of the same. And

00:08:56.440 --> 00:09:03.719
also, you know, the modeling tools and the tools for doing NLP tend to be

00:09:03.719 --> 00:09:09.760
anglo-centric. So that became a bit of an issue as well. But I think we resolved

00:09:09.760 --> 00:09:18.359
most of them. And then we got to the beta version, the one that's out now. And

00:09:18.359 --> 00:09:24.239
that's a true native app in a framework called Flutter. The programming language

00:09:24.239 --> 00:09:32.159
is called Dart. So we've sort of, we've moved the backend to the Google Cloud

00:09:32.159 --> 00:09:39.719
Firebase system. And now authentication is done by Google. And we have all the

00:09:39.719 --> 00:09:47.080
analysis done by R with a plumber API for, you know, so that the cell phone

00:09:47.080 --> 00:09:55.559
will get its information from. And then we have enhanced content

00:09:55.559 --> 00:10:01.479
recommendations. Because one of the features of this system is that if I'm

00:10:01.479 --> 00:10:06.559
teaching statistics and no one got the standard error, I may repeat that in

00:10:06.559 --> 00:10:11.039
class. But if, you know, two people did not get what a standard deviation is,

00:10:11.039 --> 00:10:17.559
I may not want to waste class time on that. And I can send them over to, you

00:10:17.559 --> 00:10:22.960
know, watch a video or something. And we try to automate some of that, which is

00:10:22.960 --> 00:10:30.280
interesting for large classes. And then we did an email interface as well.

00:10:30.280 --> 00:10:36.559
By the way, this is what it looks like now. You sign up with a QR code,

00:10:36.559 --> 00:10:40.200
which is convenient. If you're teaching online, you can show the code on the

00:10:40.200 --> 00:10:44.640
screen and they can copy it right away. It's a little more awkward if you're

00:10:44.640 --> 00:10:52.080
actually watching it on a cell phone. But, you know, it's also, you sign on with

00:10:52.080 --> 00:10:56.880
one link and it's authenticated by Google and all. And then we did, we used

00:10:56.880 --> 00:11:04.359
Blastula to send out an email report to the instructor. And this was also, you

00:11:04.359 --> 00:11:09.400
know, sort of a way to get over what I perceive to be dashboard fatigue.

00:11:09.400 --> 00:11:14.359
That people don't actually go and log into the dashboards. They, you know, but

00:11:14.359 --> 00:11:19.239
if you get it pushed into your email, maybe you actually consumed information.

00:11:19.239 --> 00:11:26.880
But that turned out not to be the case. Once we did this, we got this feedback

00:11:26.880 --> 00:11:38.919
from one of the instructors. And Cecilia and I are married. So this was

00:11:38.919 --> 00:11:45.039
not, this was a request that was difficult to ignore. And in fact, it

00:11:45.039 --> 00:11:51.599
turned out to be impossible. So we were sort of full circle. We came back to

00:11:51.599 --> 00:11:58.479
Shiny again, hoping that at least we have the instructors on Shiny, which

00:11:58.479 --> 00:12:04.440
would be a small, smaller percentage. So perhaps this is still scalable. It

00:12:04.440 --> 00:12:10.039
would be a lot worse if the instructor and 200 students would have to access

00:12:10.039 --> 00:12:16.880
the server at the same time. So this is an example from her course. And this is

00:12:16.880 --> 00:12:23.640
also an example from the same dashboard. So these are some content

00:12:23.640 --> 00:12:28.159
recommendations that the system came up with for the course that I've sort

00:12:28.159 --> 00:12:32.200
of assigned this to these specific students. That's an artificial

00:12:32.200 --> 00:12:38.200
intelligence piece that we are working on. And that's what I had for you. This

00:12:38.200 --> 00:12:43.880
is our contact info. We're happy to answer questions, both of us. So thank

00:12:43.880 --> 00:12:50.760
you.

